@Reasoning:
Integer literal -> HIR integer literal. The lexeme is captured as a
string (including any 0x/0o/0b prefix) so the parser-provided source
form is preserved for accurate downstream literal-value recovery and
diagnostic reporting.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_integer" takes context as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate integer literal to HIR

    Let hir be proc create_dictionary from Dict
    proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "_type", "python_integer"

    Let value be proc get_node_name from Parser with node
    If value is not equal to 0:
        proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "value", value
    End If

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Float literal -> HIR float literal. Source text is preserved as-is so
"1.0", "1e2", and "1." round-trip exactly. The trailing "j" imaginary
suffix (e.g. "3.14j") is recognized at the lexer and routes here with
the suffix included; downstream codegen reads the suffix to decide
between real and complex emission.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_float" takes context as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate float literal to HIR

    Let hir be proc create_dictionary from Dict
    proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "_type", "python_float"

    Let value be proc get_node_name from Parser with node
    If value is not equal to 0:
        proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "value", value
    End If

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
String literal -> HIR string literal. Source text captured includes
escape sequences (\n, \t, etc.) in their unprocessed form — escape
decoding is the responsibility of a later pass. f-strings, b-strings,
and raw-strings are distinguished by prefix metadata on the HIR node.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_string" takes context as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate string literal to HIR

    Let hir be proc create_dictionary from Dict
    proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "_type", "python_string"

    Let value be proc get_node_name from Parser with node
    If value is not equal to 0:
        proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "value", value
    End If

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
"None" -> HIR null literal. Python's None has no other forms (e.g.
"NULL" or "nil") so a single fixed-value node suffices. The HIR null
literal is the canonical representation across all source languages.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_none" takes context as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate None literal to HIR

    Let hir be proc create_dictionary from Dict
    proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "_type", "python_none"

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
"True" -> HIR boolean literal with value 1. Python's True is a
singleton; the HIR boolean literal preserves the boolean type so
downstream code can distinguish it from the integer 1 when needed for
type-narrow contexts.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_true" takes context as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate True literal to HIR

    Let hir be proc create_dictionary from Dict
    proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "_type", "python_true"

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
"False" -> HIR boolean literal with value 0. Symmetric to translate_true;
preserved as a boolean type for the same reason.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_false" takes context as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate False literal to HIR

    Let hir be proc create_dictionary from Dict
    proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "_type", "python_false"

    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parameter Translation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
One formal parameter -> HIR parameter. Captures the name, optional
type annotation, optional default value, and the parameter kind
(positional-or-keyword / positional-only / keyword-only / *args /
**kwargs). The kind flag matters because Python's calling convention
treats them differently — positional-only cannot be passed by name,
keyword-only cannot be passed positionally, etc.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_parameter" takes context as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate parameter to HIR

    Let hir be proc create_dictionary from Dict
    proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "_type", "python_parameter"

    Let name be proc get_node_name from Parser with node
    If name is not equal to 0:
        proc set_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "name", name
    End If

    Note: Type annotation (first child if present)
    Let child_count be proc get_child_count from Parser with node

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let type_node be proc get_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let type_hir be proc translate_node with context, type_node
        proc set_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "type", type_hir
    End If

    Return hir
End Process
